    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, you just said they don't need \"formal amendments or signatures immediately.\" That sounds like they can just send an email and the price goes up. If they send an email saying \"prices are up 5% because of the market\" and we don't reply, are we stuck with that price? I need to know if this clause actually gives them the power to change the rate without us explicitly signing a new document. That's a massive difference for our risk assessment.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
